review.reviewBody: I've been climbing in the mythos. While I overall love the shoe, I needed something just slightly more aggressive, with a stiffer heal. This is just that. As far as the shoes, im obsessed. These guys have already been climbing in Nevada and held up amazing, not a scratch on them. As soon as they arrived, I was able to send my 5.9 projects and definitely was able to get several more moves into my 5.10s with these shoes. The toe is grip is trustworthy, to say the least. Highly recommend.

review.reviewBody: I spent a couple of weeks debating if I should get it and fell in love with it the moment it arrived. Its exactly what I needed
review.name: Did not disappoint!

review.reviewBody: I bought this for upcoming travel, wanting a daypack that would smush into another carry-on/checked bag and have lots of gear organization and flexibility.  It has more than average internal pockets and gear organization, both accessible in the main compartment via zipper or externally (i.e., the phone pocket).  The straps and elastic cinches are all removable for use in creative ways (see the Youtube clip featuring Bev), including using as a chest-mounted bag between two backpack straps.  The internal storage is big enough for my mirrorless camera and a 1L collapsible water bottle...supposedly it'll fit a XS camera cube, but that seems overkill for my use case.  Materials are lightweight but feel robust.  Overall, seems legit and would recommend if the size/form factor fit your need.
review.name: Highly adaptable sling for travel

review.reviewBody:
Added a small tech pouch inside and its becoming the most versatile sling bag in town !
I can bring my edc and when I need them I can bring my iPad or my action cam with a pod and whatever I need.
review.name: Great !

review.reviewBody: You can pack it very small but it is strong and flexible. Love the magnetic pocket, straps and front pocket with key holder
review.name: Just right

review.reviewBody: I love this 7L sling bag.  It is exactly what I have needed for a while.  Not too big or small.  Great for the extra stuff and a lens.  Nice outside pocket for a cell phone.  Long shoulder crossbody strap is also a perfect and comfortable length.  Well done Peak Design!
review.name: Love this bag!

review.reviewBody: Recently purchased my  Peak Design Outdoor Sling 7L in Cloud as a replacement of my old Stubble & Co cross body sling and couldn't be happier, the compact design expendable to 7L is a versatile and stylish sling bag. Whether youre a photographer needing quick access to your gear or just someone who enjoys outdoor activities, this sling meet all my urban and outdoor needs beautifully no longer require to carry out a backpack as well as a sling when traveling. I highly recommend it to anyone considering a new bag for travel or daily use!
review.name: Small but mighty

review.reviewBody: Great idea, great product. Glad i backed the project
review.name: Great sling

review.reviewBody:
7L is a lot of space and the bag is incredibly lightweight, plenty of pockets and features to make it super useful for traveling and general purpose use.
The issue only arise when the xxs packing cube is used, is great to be able to swap them but they're very thick and fit little equipment, it would be nice to have a larger capacity insert for cameras even if it had thinner walls. Without the insert there are no dividers so you can fit a large camera/lens but not two smaller lenses as they would bump on each other.
review.name: Great for travel, meh for cameras

review.reviewBody: Ive had this for about a week and it absolutely works for my lifestyle
review.name: I just love the simplicity of use.

review.reviewBody:
I bought this with the Xsmall camera cube. Before I purchased this I was on a vacation to Utah and doing a lot of hiking with just my camera and peak camera strap. In some areas it was really slippery terrain and I was worried about falling with no protection for my camera thus purchasing this set up. Also liked having sacra room to carry my glasses and sun glasses with extra cards and batteries. 
Great product and can hardly wait to try it out on my next adventure.
review.name: Great new product

review.reviewBody: Great for running / trail running in late winter here in Wisco. Just the right amount of warmth and breathability. Fit is fantastic for the most part.. fingers were a bit long to start but after breaking in, they're great.
review.name: Awesome late winter glove

review.reviewBody: These gloves fit perfectly! They are warm, but also allow me to operate my camera smoothly outside in the winter! A lot of touchscreen gloves don't work well, but these are precise and comfortable!
review.name: Awesome gloves!

review.reviewBody: These are night lightweight gloves, which is what I was looking for - just something to fit under my larger mitts when hiking/snowboarding. I also wanted a glove that would shed snow and block wind while I'm hiking and not wearing my mitts. My last pair of lightweight gloves did not shed snow or block wind at all and would get wet/cold really quickly so I always had to carry a couple pairs with me when hiking. I went for a hike today after a snowstorm and the snow falling from the trees shed right off them so I love them in that regard. Granted they aren't waterproof so if you go digging around in the snow they will get wet. It was ~20 degrees out on my hike today and they were plenty warm while I was hiking. However, if you're planning to get these for the touchscreen compatibility, I would look elsewhere. I could barely get them to work well enough to enter my passcode to open my phone, but couldn't get them to do anything other than that (even that was a struggle). Not a deal breaker for me, I just pull my thumb out when I need to use my phone which is what I've always had to do, but wanted to give a warning to those thinking they'd be able to use their phone without taking the gloves off. But maybe it's because I have a screen protector on my phone which is another layer between the glove and phone? 5 stars as just a liner glove, but giving a 3 star rating because of the claimed touchscreen compatibility which does not seem to work for me.
review.name: Nice lightweight gloves, not touchscreen compatible

review.reviewBody: Finally! A pair of light gloves that are warm, fit well, and actually work perfectly on touchscreens! Thank you.
review.name: Love these gloves!

review.reviewBody: I think these are great. I was able to keep them on during my jog the whole time without having to remove them. They're the perfect weight for mid to low 40's. Haven't tried code yet
review.name: Excellent so far

review.reviewBody: Great gloves for high exertion in moderately cold temperatures. They manage sweat well and do not overheat when running a hard workout, but keep hands warm all the way to the tips of the fingers. The new low profile snap system to connect the two gloves together when not in use is much nicer than the old clips!
review.name: Great versatile liner gloves

review.reviewBody: Love this one. One of the best all around performers and feels great on the river.
review.name: Love it.

review.reviewBody: This life jacket is not only the most comfortable floatation I have ever used and also the most kind to the environment. Its floatation is supplied by Kapok, a natural fiber that is much softer than traditional petroleum-derived foam and contours to your body and bodys movements much better. It feels like wearing a pillow and its fleece-lined hand warmer pockets further the coziness of this PFD. The three side-straps allow for a uniformly snug fit that also combines with the softness of the Kapok to contour to the wearer nicely and allows a broad range of motion. Having paddled my Necky Looksha IV sea kayak with this PFD for the last 18 months, Ive found that I have enough mobility for a good eskimo roll and aggressive paddling without any noticeable under arm abrasion or other motion limitation. For the type of paddling I do in relatively chilly water, it works great. The only critique I have of this particular PFD is that it can be pretty warm on hot days, especially if youre not getting wet (mine is also black so that might be part of it). Overall, this is a fantastic PFD.
review.name: I LOVE THIS PFD!

review.reviewBody:
I was right on the border for the fit as I am bigger in the chest area, but smaller everywhere else so I chanced it got a size SM instead of Medium. It was a little tight to zip up, but once zipped in, it  fit perfect. I swam a couple rapids with it and it did great keeping me afloat. 
Movement is great as well, love the feeling of being able to move. 
The front zip pocket fits a large phone perfectly and I enjoy the zipped hand pockets. Keep in mind, none of the pockets are water proof.
review.name: Fit and function

review.reviewBody: Really comfy, and probably makes me float. Nice color
review.name: Comfy

review.reviewBody: First, the comfort. They aren't lying when they say that the Kapok fill in the Ceiba is ultra comfortable. It really is like wearing a down jacket as a life jacket. Literally hugs your body like a warm embrace. Add in the simplicity and front zip entry, and this is now the best and most versatile life jacket in my garage. Bonus points for using a bluesign shell and continuing leading the industry away from toxic materials.
review.name: The Best All Around Life Jacket Ever?

review.reviewBody: With the combination of the all new Bluesign approved shell material, Kapok, and PE foam - this is both one of the most comfortable and the most sustainable PFD in the world.  Win-Win.

review.reviewBody:
The backpack is a solid choice for anyone looking to embark on a 2-3 day short trip. The quality of the bag is undoubtedly top-notch, which is evident in its sturdy build. However, this does come with a downside - the backpack is on the heavier side, making it more suitable for individuals with a taller stature or those with a bit more muscle to carry it around comfortably.

Despite the weight, the backpacks organizational system is where it truly shines. It offers a plethora of compartments and pockets, allowing for the efficient packing of everything from a laptop to clothes and toiletries. The dedicated laptop sleeve is a nice touch, providing a snug and secure place for your tech gear.

The backpacks design is also very user-friendly, with ergonomic shoulder straps that distribute weight evenly and a chest strap that helps to stabilize the load. The material used is durable and resistant to wear and tear, making it a great investment for frequent travelers.

Overall, if youre in the market for a backpack that can handle a few days worth of essentials and is built to last, this one is definitely worth considering. Just keep in mind the weight and ensure its a good fit for your body type.

review.reviewBody:
This is a great Rope, I'm from Mexico and we don't get these brand that easy. It is a very convenient rope due to the low weight and the static characteristics.

Just beware that this rope is very thing compared to the majority of the market, I would recommend using a rappel device that allows you to introduce more friction to control better your descend.

That would be my only advice  on how to use it properly. Overall the rope looks great, love the color.
review.name: Good rope, just beware the diameter

review.reviewBody: I don't know anything about canyoning. Never done it. I do know about rigging and emergencies, and when it comes to those this is good stuff to have in the arsenal. It's light enough to carry enough to matter, and strong enough to trust when needs must. Would I use this when I know I may whip? No. And when abseiling with no support, doubling up is my preferred option. But for continuous load situations it's plenty good, in my opinion. And if it's the only rope you have it's way better then no rope at all, and the rope you're most likely to have is the rope which weighs the least. In my experience anyway. It's also my opinion that 100' of rope is the bare minimum worth carrying if you're gonna carry rope. And 100' of this stuff is very light. Relatively speaking.

It also compresses the bag in a weird way in the middle, especially if it's not all the way full. #2 - the sizing is a bit weird IMO. According to the size chart I'm a S/M by waist size (5'10" 163lbs, 31 waist) however the shoulder straps end up a bit shorter than I'd prefer when wearing it. It works, its just not totally ideal. Going up to the larger size I'd be worried that the waist wouldn't get tight enough. Anyway, overall I'm satisfied with the bag. Has all the right features and it's super durable and light weight. review.reviewBody:
There are some things I do like about these skins - the weight, the feel and the ease at which you can pull skins off of your skis.

However, all of the positives don't outweigh a big negative for me, which has been very frustrating. Every time I've used them - every time, multiple times per outing - the plastic clip on the tail comes off of my ski. I understand this is probably because the tails of my backcountry skis are round, and don't have a notch-shaped tail for the clips to stay in place, but for the price of these skins, I don't know why there wouldn't be a more reliable bar option if desired for the tails of your skins to stay in place. The front feels super secure, and I've had skins in the past that have bars that go across both the tips and tails.

I've also adjusted the back clip per the instructions and tested out other levels, and still not had any luck. 

Overall, I was super stoked to get new gear for the backcountry this season, and I'm planning on finding a different pair of skins for next season.
review.name: Tail clip is a problem

review.reviewBody: These skins have great grip, and are lighter weight than a full synthetic. They glide really nicely. My favorite feature is how packable they are, the skin is not nearly as rigid as the black diamond ascension skins. They also resist glopping better than the black diamond ascension.
review.name: Light, packable and great glide.

review.reviewBody:
It pays to spend a few extra dollars and get an 100% mohair skin like these Pomoca Climb Pros. 

I love the glide and grip that these offer over synthetic and blended skins, especially with Pomoca's superior hardware and glue (that somehow sticks to your ski, but rips easily). 

While synthetic options will be more durable, I've toured heavily on some Climb Pros for two seasons and have yet to notice anything other than normal wear and tear. 

While I'd set my skis up with any of Pomoca's skins, the Climb Pro's are always my top pick when I'm getting a new pair of touring skis set up. With the included skin trimming tool, you can have these ready to tour within minutes of them arriving.
review.name: Best of the best!

review.reviewBody: I bought this so I could ski resorts and have more protection against Covid. The good news is that it fits my head comfortably and stays snug. The bad news is that the filters are practically useless. They?re super thin and hard to insert into the pocket. And once they are in place you can?t move your mask or it will wrinkle the filter and drive you crazy. The mask itself is also super thin. On a cold day you can see plenty of your breath coming out of it.  I?ve also tried wearing it without a filter underneath a second traditional over the ears face mask for extra protection and that seems to work ok.
review.name: It?s just ok.

review.reviewBody: Bought this for skiing . The mask insert always falls out rendering the mask just about useless. Stay away.

review.reviewBody:
Snug fit reusable and washable. And the multi-layers makes it work well for any ski resort (or similar) place that requires a mask that has 2+ layers. I.e. when your old thin Buff that you used to wear skiing doesn't cut it with the new COVID rules.

I have a large head and stand 6'3". It's snug, but not uncomfortably so. the adjustable straps help here.
review.name: good for exercise, multi-layered.

review.reviewBody:
I bought this for skiing during COVID.  My first impressions upon opening it was that it was super thin.  Not only was the mask fabric very thin so is the filter - to the point that it is hard to properly insert the filter into the mask.  I heard a litmus test for bad masks is that if you are able to blow a candle out with it then it is not safe to wear.  With this mask I was definitely able to make the flame flicker.  All that is to say, I think this mask would be great for folks looking for a cardio friendly mask that might not be as safe as others (but I think it is safer than just a single layer of a normal buff).

I have had one day of resort skiing with this mask.  It worked better than I expected.  My goggles didn't fog.  The temps were on the warm side (28-32F); the mask never froze over nor did it get so wet to be uncomfortable or seem compromised.  I'll be interested to see how it performs at lower temps.  Also, the head straps didn't fit me as well at the picture but I do think that this design is better when wearing a helmet than over-the-ear masks (not sure if I'm the only one who has had issues with ones helmet sliding their mask off as they put it on).

All and all, I'm happy with it so far.
review.name: Bought for skiing during COVID

review.reviewBody: I've been waiting for this to be restocked in my size for 3 months, and was happy that it became available. The fabric is beautiful and soft, and I feel that this will be a good transition from winter through the endless New England spring. The fasteners - a tiny button with a corresponding teeny loop - are awkwardly placed and I'm wondering if they will survive. Because the fabric is soft and stretchy, I'm expecting where the button is attached will eventually start to wear because it's not reinforced, yet is holding up a lot of fabric. I'm layering it now with the Everyday Exploration Merino Short Sleeve shirt, which works well because the shirt has elbow-length sleeves (no bunching). Under both, I have the Merino Sport Tank Dress. I actually feel a bit stylish!
review.name: Beautiful fabric!

review.reviewBody: This is a super cozy sweater but the fit and closure is awkward. It's literally a rectangle with sleeves sewn onto it. I'm a size small in literally everything and this fits a little too tight across the back. Since the material has good stretch it is still wearable. The closure points around the neck/on top of the shoulders are also incredibly awkward to fasten. It would have been nice if there was a closure point either lower or closer to the front of the sweater, since it will open up and flap about if you do anything besides sit in a chair all day. Despite all those criticisms, the sweater is as comfy as all get out and I wear it a ton already.
review.name: Super cozy but a bit awkward

review.itemreviewed: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles
review.reviewBody:
I have used these poles for multiple adventures. From rugged mountain hikes over talus to sea side beach hikes.  They have performed well catching what could have been a fall. The grip design is quite nice as when going down I will palm the top of the grip. And just under it are two slight indentation that two fingers dovetail into adding stability. Only once have I had a problem collapsing the pole. Not sure why but one would not release until I gave it a good tug. Normally a slight tug works. 

I did take these on a technical desert hike with lots scrambling. In the future I would use my older Makalu poles for such hikes as they see a lot of abuse. The aluminum will just hold up better. Otherwise they are now my goto trekking pole.
review.name: My goto trekking pole

review.reviewBody: Really glad to have very packable sticks to use a week to months out of town. I can occasionally notice squeaky inner connections while walking, but usually don't notice the sound. Great poles! Love the folding and locking system. So happy to have them: )

review.itemreviewed: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles
review.reviewBody: These are the best trekking poles money can but. They are feather light, sturdy and rigid, supremely comfy grip straps. On the fly length adjustments are easy. The collapsible function is clever and works flawlessly. Theyre an investment for sure, but literally as good as it gets!
review.name: Best poles money can buy

review.itemreviewed: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles
review.reviewBody: These poles are durable and light. The grips are comfortable. Sometimes, the poles will get stuck in mud and the joint will separate slightly, and snap quickly back into place. This doesnt bother me personally, and it has not impacted the functionality. They are easily stow-able. It is worth it to buy quality poles, and these fit the bill.

review.name: Great hiking / trekking poles.

review.reviewBody: The best hiking poles Ive ever owned. They collapse easily and a feather light.

review.itemreviewed: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles
review.reviewBody: Great trekking poles, love the adjustability. Took a minute to figure out how to collapse them after assembling, but the process is easy once you get the hang of it.

review.itemreviewed: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles
review.reviewBody: I owned these poles for three months. They were used on only three hikes, two day, and one 91 mile through hike. By mile 67 of the hike, one of the poles snapped when I slipped. I attempted to repair them with tape. Unfortunately, they broke again, this time jilting my balance on a steel talus slope, and I lost my grip on the pole. It fell into a narrow role between rocks and although I tried, it was unrecoverable. Unfortunately, these being bought as a pro deal nulls their warranty. I had a pair of black diamond carbons that lasted six years. I absolutely would not recommend these to others.
review.name: Not durable
comment: Sorry to hear about the breakage of your pole and the loss of another into the abyss. We pride ourselves on making the strongest and most durable product on the market and we are disappointed to hear that your poles broke during your adventure. Unfortunately, there are times when poles fail in the field due to the perfect combination of forces being applied in the wrong spot. We will share your review with our engineers as we are always seeking feedback from consumers to help us continue to produce the most durable products possible.

name: Black Series FX Carbon Trekking Poles

review.reviewBody:
I had watched every review of the Matador small and large towels on the internet.  Backcountry had both items in their inventory, so I ordered one of each for my husband and myself.

The order came as expected with excellent tracking and communication. It wasn't a quick ship, but that was OK.  The problem was that ONE of the large towels was in a taped up container, probably had been returned after getting moldy, and it probably "infected" the other three towels in shipping.  

I should have returned everything right on the spot.  But I was in a hurry.  I was going out the door right by my washer, and I had quickly removed all of them from their packaging, tossed the packaging and then tossed all four times and their covers into the wash.  It was only as I was closing the door that I caught a whiff.  Mold, mildew to the heights.  I'm deathly allergic to various molds.

I prayed  right then and there that a wash with extra rinse would get rid of the problem.  

No way.  

I then washed all four with bleach.  No better.  

I soaked them in vinegar for an hour; then baking soda for an hour.  Washed again.  Not as smelly, but when I "whiffed" I got the dizzy feeling some molds give me.

I'm currently putting all out in the sun for hours.  Yesterday's sun treatment didn't work--got the dizzy feeling from the sniff test.  But I shall keep trying.

I'm not asking for a refund.  I was stupid.  As soon as I saw the taped up package, I should have investigated.  But Backcountry should never have accepted that return from the person who sent the product back moldy and they sure should not have sent it on to me.  

And since this product is advertised as "antimicrobial", I'm wondering how well any of the towels would have done on our upcoming trip anyway.
review.name: A returned item ruined my entire order

review.reviewBody: Bought these for hiking in the mountains in Georgia. After 7 days in a row of wearing them, I can honestly say they are the most comfortable hiking boots I've ever worn. The toe box is wide, which anyone who has ever worn hiking boots knows is essential to not have your toes pinched. The soles are cushy and I do not have any foot pain, when I do after wearing most shoes due to plantar fasciitis. I did not have any break-in period on these shoes. I wore them out of the box and no blisters or discomfort. I have worn them on rainy days over slippery rocks, on steep inclines and clay/dusty trails, in muddy pastures and long grass. These shoes performed well through it all. I have gotten so many complements and everyone always says "Oh, I didn't know Teva made hiking boots." They do run slightly small as I normally wear size 9 and ordered size 9.5 in these.
review.name: Must have

review.reviewBody: I have had problems with Morton's neuromas in both feet for years and have tried on more boots then I can count. These are so comfortable that I also wear them now when I am walking my dog. Highly recommend
review.name: Comfort!!

review.reviewBody: The only thing I can say is they are at least attractive on your feet.. my foot would slide around in them on hikes... not enough support and would hurt your feet, oh and they are not water proof.. I spent to much money on these.
review.name: No

review.reviewBody: I just wore these boots to climb a mountain and these boots kept my feet dry and comfortable. The wide toe box is my absolute favorite. I got zero blisters, but I was wearing wool socks. I recommend sizing up. In regular shoes I wear 7.5. Boots are normally size 8 but these I'm wearing a 8.5 for thick socks and room for my toes to move. I love that these wear more like tennis shoes rather than boots, but provides the sturdiness of a boot.
review.name: I would totally buy these boots again!

review.reviewBody: I'm a Vietnam era Vet so you can guess my age, and before I found TEVA every shoe I'd ordered hurt my feet from day one. These shoes were worn the first day for a day of doctor's appointments, shopping and delivering a TV to a friend. When I got home as I started undressing I realized I had worn these beautiful boots all day and not a SINGLE pinch or pain infllicting fold. If you need something to wear on your feet, buy TEVA. I have their Symic hiking sandals, midform boots and these. My feet LOVE them!!
review.name: There's nothing better for feet that love to walk

review.reviewBody: I don't usually leave reviews but I've never had a comfier hiking shoe. I work for state and national parks so I'm on my feet all day long and these left me pleasantly surprised with how great they are. I read a review that the toe part was very big so I was almost turned away but I'm glad I didn't because I realized in past boots I've purchased they were uncomfortable cramming my toes together. The straps on the ankle I like as well because they feel very secure while the boot doesn't actually feel tight around your foot at all. I walk all day long and more than less I actually wear them on my day off too! Plus they're super cute.
review.name: Im considering buying another pair in case they sell out

review.reviewBody: These are the only walking/hiking boots that I can wear. I have tried others over the years and I love the Grandview GTX. Thank you making these for me!
review.name: I will be buying this product again when I need a new pair.

review.reviewBody: I'm mostly going on 1-2 mile walks for now. But am hoping to try some hiking in parks soon. I have rheumatoid arthritis with painful ankles and toes that can't stand being squished. These boots feel wonderful very cushioned,great arch support for my flat feet and my toes are no longer numb and painful. Can't wait to wear them crossing streams with their waterproof properties.
review.name: These are wonderful!

review.reviewBody: I tried these on without socks and they are the best fitting shoes I've ever worn! Very lightweight but sturdy and rugged. The inside is so soft and the heel is slightly slanted towards the toe so it naturally moves your foot forward, I haven't hiked in them but imagine they are wonderful. I'm buying another pair!
review.name: I don't want to take them off!

review.reviewBody: Best hiking boot ever. These boots are impressive. Good space in toebox and very comfortable with awesone stability. True to size. They feel like you're wearing sneakers instead of a boot!! Will buy a second pair. Highly recommend.
review.name: Super Comfortable

review.reviewBody: This is my second time buying this helmet.  I have a Lazer G1 mips as well, but I prefer this helmet over it. This is a perfect fit for my round bald head. My first one is old and the lock is broken. The Lazer was the initial replacement, but I felt the need to come back.
review.name: 2nd One, Favorite Lid

review.reviewBody: Has worked out great for me.  Good balance of cost and function.  MIPS is a good safety feature.
review.name: LIKE IT

review.reviewBody:
Two other Giro lids have already protected me in crashes so with the 3rd one getting old I wanted to replace it with a MIPS model.  The added MIPS protection does require some small differences in shape and fit but they are less noticeable than I expected, especially since I watch a lot of Pro-Tour races and that's just how helmets look now.

My head measured 58 cm which put me near the upper end of the 55-59 cm range for a Medium but even if I add a sweat band there's still some adjustment space leftover.  The vents are small but many and ventilation didn't seem to be a problem on a 2 hour ride in the mid-eighties.  I also looked at the Bell Stratus but it's large vents seemed to invite sunburn on my scalp.
review.name: Got MIPS and Good Looking

review.reviewBody: This is a nice looking helmet but sits way too low on my head. It sits so low that the ear stems on my eyewear will not sit under the sides of the helmet without pushing up on the helmet causing a poor fit and ill fitting glasses. This is the 2nd Giro helmet, Agilis, I've tried in the last two months that does this. I have a Giro Aeon that fits great and was hoping one of these two would be a good replacement. Apparently not.
review.name: Poor fit and design

review.reviewBody: Great helmet...Ive ridden/raced bikes for a long time, all with a Giro helmet. Fits my head, looks good, great form/function. I needed to replace my old one due to a recent crash.
review.name: Giro all the way

review.reviewBody: My last helmet was offered by Specialized and I loved it.  It was comfortable, cool and came with various additional reflecting tape strips that you could put on as you wished.  (I added a couple of pieces to the front and the back and, in low light, they really helped.)  I did a bunch of RAGBRAI's with it and it performed very well.  However, I was nagged by my ride buddy to get a new one - as it was 9 years old.  My local bike shop echoed that sentiment so I looked at several brands and got the Syntax in yellow & white.  It was the only helmet in the shop that I liked right off and fit very well - Size L.  I also was pleased that it rated highly in Va. Tech's helmet ratings getting 5 stars for safety.  So far, so good.  It happens that I have two pairs of Giro shoes (white & black) and they also fit and perform very well.
review.name: Great Replacement for an Aging Helmet

review.reviewBody:
Just purchased the white/citron Syntax in size M.  Prior helmet was a Giro Saros, a good helmet which lasted until I could no longer order replacement sweat pads.  I was already a fan of the Roc Loc retention system, and the Saros had good ventilation.  Here's what I like even better about the Syntax:
1. MIPS!
2. Fit - the Syntax is a deeper helmet, it covers more of your head and fits better as a result.  With the Rock Lock adjusted properly, it does not move when I shake my head from side to side - even without the chin strap.
3. Straps - made of a thinner and lighter webbing, they secure the helmet better and more comfortably than the Saros did.
4. Color - the white/citron looks cool and adds visibility.  No matter what kit I wear, my socks and gloves are high vis yellow and this matches.

The helmet seems to be slightly heavier than the Saros, but not by much.  Honestly - when I'm riding, I barely feel the helmet and that's as good as it gets.
review.name: Great road helmet in every way

name: Syntax Mips Helmet

review.reviewBody: To startonce I get warmed up I might sweat a fair bit. It seems that all winter packs have a padded back panel these days so there is no airflow around my back & a fair bit of thermal protection. For winter adventures Ive always wanted a jacket that provides warmth & water resistance only where Im actually exposed. This jacket is exactly what Ive been looking for. It is a slightly slim fit which is good for me because in the times I would need it Ill only have a base layer under it anyway. Super stoked that OR nailed this one.
review.name: Finallythe right clothing for wearing a pack

review.reviewBody: I live at elevation, where weather conditions can change fast (and wind is common). I've worn this jacket in a variety of conditions so far: rain/snow mix at 40 degrees, < sub-freezing temps and sunny, dark and 32 degrees. It's kept me warm without overheating, blocked the wind, and kept me dry during light/moderate precipitation. It's lightweight and packs up small, and is my new fav running item! It feels like it might run just a tad bit small in my opinion, so if you want a thicker layer under it, I might suggest sizing up.
review.name: Completely love this jacket!

review.reviewBody: I winter hike a lot in the white mountains of New Hampshire and I love this layer! It's perfect for ascents over my 300 weight wool shirt. I rarely sweat in it or need more than those 2 layers. If I do sweat it evaporates very quickly. It's very thin and lightweight however I barely need an additional layer in higher elevations. I have worn this in temps ranging from 10-30 degrees F. It's amazing. I love the windbreaker aspect of it bc it either surprise snows or you brush up against trees while hiking and don't get wet. You stay so warm with the fleece lining. Still can't believe how thin it is.
review.name: Amazing workable winter layer

review.reviewBody: bought this hoody because my favorite clothing item the OR ascendant hoody has been discontinued and I'm on search for a replacement. This is not it. The sleeves feel both bulky and not insulating. AND The jacket must be worn with a vest as the back is non insulated. The fit is trimmer and less cozy/comfy than the ascendant and the zipper is chintzy itty bitty and a pain to use especially as compared to the ascendant. I still wear the jacket running with a vest over it but I certainly won't be buying a second one just in case...
review.name: Not a substitute for my beloved ascendant hoody

review.reviewBody: Great for all cooler temps. layer up and use in winter. great stretch and quick drying. True to size
review.name: GAME CHANGER

review.reviewBody: So versatile. I wear this in 50 degree weather over a t-shirt to hike, or in 10 degree weather over a baselayer to xc ski. It layers under a shell well too. Breathable, but cuts the wind when biking or skiing. The hood fits super well, alone or under a helmet. And my favorite part... a chest pocket!! Not enough women's jackets have them.
review.name: Love

review.reviewBody: I've had this piece out for a couple of runs now, and I really like it. It's quite warm- I was a bit too warm today in 2C sunny weather - but it sheds heat well, and I was glad to have the warmth when the sky clouded over. This will be a jacket that I break out at 0C or below, personally, but I run hot. Lots of pockets, which are nice. Very soft and comfortable; flattering fit without being restrictive. Fit true to size for me (5'9" 160lb.) Only things I would change: it would be great if there was a drawcord at the hem, both to snug it up in colder/windy conditions and to stop the contents of the pockets from bouncing as much; and I find the wrists aren't stretchy enough to pull over a watch without a bit of effort.

review.reviewBody: I bought these boots because I needed some cuter rain boots in Ireland/England and these fit all of my requirements. I wore these boots almost every day of the two weeks I was in Europe and they held up so well! They kept my feet dry and were so comfortable, I didn't mind wearing them all the time. I had a severe ankle injury last year (involved surgery) and these made me feel so stable, even on all of those lovely cobblestone streets, and my ankle didn't bother me. I will recommend wearing them before taking them on a big trip; they do some rubbing around the ankles where I wasn't used to having shoes that height. I would highly recommend these boots!!

review.reviewBody: This shoe is a marvel of modern misengineering. It's mid sole and toe appear to have been modeled to fit a club-flippered walrus. Paired with a flimsy elastic heel, one cannot walk 3 steps without their foot coming dislodged - even if you buy a half-size down as I had. Utter garbage. I will only grace Teva the relief of accepting my return if they also commit to planting a forest to offset the ecological disaster of this shoe line.
review.name: Absolute trash shoe

review.reviewBody: I've bought 2 pairs of these shoes in the less than a year, and here's why. They are great...to begin with. But with just a short time, the heel of the sole starts to peel off of the bottom. My first pair did it in less than 2 months, and my 2nd pair lasted maybe 3 months before it started happening. And I am not rough on my shoes by any means. I work a simple cashier job and I make sure I'm using my hands to take them off rather than using my other foot. Absolutely ridiculous for the price of these that the sole starts to peel off so quickly. It's very disappointing too because I absolutely LOVE these shoes otherwise. They have been the only thing I can find that don't cause me pain in my back and feet.
review.name: Great shoes with 1 HUGE FLAW

review.reviewBody: I have to send it back. They are too big. Ordered the correct size 39/40 for a female. But that is not the correct sizing for this shoe USA size 9 is not Size 42 European. It should be equal to 40.
review.name: Man sizes instead of woman sizes

review.reviewBody: The thin brown tread is peeling off the soles of both left and right heel areas by ~1 inch, so far. And I've only been wearing them around the house for about 10 weeks! Clearly defective. Unfortunately, because they happened to be on sale when I bought them, I can't exchange them for the same shoe?! Defective is defective regardless of the price. Do I have to wait for them to go a sale again to get an exchange? So ridiculous.
review.name: Separating tread from soles on both heels after 10 weeks!

review.reviewBody: Wore these to wear inside the house when it's cold in so cal and so like 2 months out of the year. The heal has ripped after a season or two on one side and other side looks like it'll rips soon. The inner sole go through the rip so they are basically trash at this point. It's a shame cause the bottom of the shoes looks brand new. Wish they'd make it more durable or allow the shoes to be used even with the rip.
review.name: Ripped heal!!

review.reviewBody: The design is very pretty, the shoes are comfortable but maybe a little too soft for me. I'm keeping them anyway to try them out
review.name: Nice but a little too soft for me

review.reviewBody: I would not recommend these shoes. Within two weeks, the soles began peeling off of both shoes. We reached out to customer service and they said that we'd have to send them back for evaluation, and then they would determine whether or not they could replace them. Or I could buy new ones and if they determined that the should were faulty, then they could refund me. They also stated that this process takes 10 business days. The shoes that we purchased are no longer in stock so if we wanted replacements, then we have to wait for them to be back in stock. We purchased shoes that we intended to wear and now we will have to be without shoes for an indefinite amount of time. Because of the poor quality and even poorer customer service response, I would tell you to save your money and not purchase these shoes.
review.name: Shoes fell apart within two weeks of wear

review.reviewBody:
If you're on the hunt for the ultimate all-purpose shoe, look no further than the Teva ReEMBER. These bad boys have become my go-to for just about everything, and let me tell you, they do not disappoint!

First off, let's talk convenience. Who wants to fuss with laces when you're just dashing out to grab some milk or taking out the trash in record time? Not me! That's where these babies swoop in to save the day. Slip 'em on, and you're good to go.

And when it comes to versatility, oh boy, these shoes are the MVPs. Need to ditch your kicks and hop into ski boots in a flash? Done. Heading out camping and want a comfy shoe for lounging around the fire or making those midnight bathroom runs? These are your guys.

I've rocked two pairs of these babies, and let me tell you, they're built to last. Even with my habit of wearing shoes until they're practically begging for retirement, these hold up like champs. The only (big) catch? They only come in full sizes. If you're like me and fall in between sizes, I'd recommend sizing down for a snug fit.

Now, let's talk downsides. Traction? Eh, it's okay, but not mind-blowing. And as for water resistance, well, let's just say they're not exactly built to be submarines. But hey, every rose has its thorn, right?

In a nutshell, these shoes are not just footwear  they're a lifestyle. Durable, versatile, and perfect for any adventure life throws your way. Plus, they make killer gifts. Trust me, your pals will thank you.
review.name: Step Into Versatility

review.reviewBody: I've been wearing them for over a year now to all of my college classes and they are very comfortable and still look brand new despite some dirt. I also wear them around the campsite but this past time a stray ember burned a pretty sizable hole in the top, but they did protect my foot. Will have to purchase again.
review.name: I love these

review.reviewBody: I have another pair of these slippers and like them so much that I got another pair while they were on sale.
review.name: Very Comfortable Slippers

name: ReEMBER - Men's

review.reviewBody:
It is a sturdy, well-crafted knife for those who prefer durability and reliability in outdoor gear. I was genuinely surprised by its sharpness, and I hope the blade holds its edge well, maintaining efficiency during extended use.

The main reason I purchased it was its full-tang construction. I appreciate the minimalist design without a traditional handle material. This design choice not only makes it easy to clean but also ensures there are no cracks or joints where the handle might eventually break or loosen over time.

However, it's slightly heavier than I expected. While I like the knife's functionality, I probably won't use it for backpacking. If youre looking to shave every possible ounce from your pack, this might feel a little too hefty. I might get their Detour Stainless Steel Paring Knife as a lighter option for backpacking.
review.name: Sharp, durable, but slightly heavy

review.reviewBody: The size is very portable, the edge guard attached firmly and the knife is very sharp. I like the grip of the handle and the ability to use different grips for different cutting chores. The thin blade easily chops vegetables, slices cheese, and trims meat. Perfect for camping, office, or RV.
review.name: I absolutely love this kitchen knife.

review.reviewBody:
These are my favorite lockers for almost every use. They're light, strong, easy to lock and unlock... but do not use them on ascenders or any device that may want this to rotate around (such as a micro traction or Spoc...etc.) they have a more angled curve at the tip, which makes it hard for devices to move around.
My partner used one of these on the top hole of his ascender, and it got stuck because of that reason. After 10 mins of hitting it with a rock it finally came unstuck.

That said, I bring these up on every multipitch. The nose is tiny and you can fit multiple of them in a single bolt hanger. Love it. Would recommend to my friends, with the caveat mentioned above.
review.name: Perfect for almost every use

review.reviewBody:
I bought these to lighten my gear. And they do that just fine!

But I really like them regardless. For the size, they are strong (22kn) enough and the gate is pretty wide. 

Also, I tend to over tighten the screw on occasion.  A few other brands can be a real bear to loosen; these don't have that problem.

review.reviewBody: I have wanted this parka for years since I first saw it. I finally broke down and bought it with the Black Friday discount.  I know the reviews are mixed on this parka, however, for me it is perfect. It is extremely lightweight and yet very warm. I almost feel like Im wearing nothing at all.  Keep in mind this jacket is rated for 40-60 so if you want something warmer keep this in mind.  I initially got a medium and exchanged it for small.  FYI, I am 57  126 lbs and only plan to wear medium weight sweaters underneath.  My only criticism is that I wish it was about 2 inches shorter like the previous version of this parka. review.reviewBody: The Patagonia Nano Puff Parka for women was the jacket I'd been searching for:  Lightweight, no bulk, two-way zipper, nice lines, nice color (new navy), covers my seat, and finally, a jacket without a hood!  I typically wear sizes 2 or 4 but given the reviews, I ordered a size S (4-6).  The jacket on its own is a close fit, but when layered over a lightweight sweater, the sleeve and the bodice were too tight.  The jacket on its own is not warm enough for the northeast - I live in wool all winter.  One would think Patagonia sized their clothing for layering and rugged women (with a little muscle).   I tried on a size M in a nearby store but it was way too long in the sleeve and overall length.   Please Patagonia, correct the flaw in this otherwise perfect jacket!  BTW, Backcountry was excellent to work with!
review.name: Perfect parka but sizing is flawed!

review.reviewBody:
This seatpost solves the issues I have had with the other competitors. It is lighter and has the right level of travel for the rough roads around my area. The setback is also consistent through the travel so that bike fit remains true. The elastomer does create a little bit of a bounce feeling when returning from a big bump, but not something that is bothersome. In fact, after a short ride, I no longer was aware of any bounce feeling on rough surfaces. 
I have used the original eesilk and loved it! But it just wasn?t enough travel for some of the rougher roads. The shockstop seatpost is on my other bike. It is wonderful, but heavier and requires lots of fiddling to set up and tune. 
If you have a gravel bike or ride occasionally on rough roads, this seatpost is worth twice its weight in gold for the comfort factor. The weight increase compared to a stiff carbon post is negligible when compared to the energy you save from no longer having to brace for every little road impact. Saved energy means you can go faster and farther and get home less sore and fatigued! 
Get it! You won?t regret it.
review.name: Best suspension seat for all road riding
